            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Though his surname spoke of Japan, Kevin Saito\u2019s upbringing was pure 1980s Northern California suburbia. The son of a quiet, second-generation Japanese American architect and a boisterous White elementary school teacher from Oregon, Kevin grew up feeling more connected to his mother\u2019s outgoing nature than his father\u2019s stoic reserve. His childhood was filled with bike rides, skateboarding, and a fascination with album art and magazine layouts, a visual language that felt more accessible than the unspoken history of his father\u2019s family.\n\nThis passion led him to the California College of the Arts for a degree in Graphic Design. He graduated in 2001, directly into the ashes of the dot-com bust. The first few years were a lesson in creative survival: freelance print jobs, designing menus for struggling restaurants, and eventually, building rudimentary websites. It was here he discovered his true calling wasn't just making things look good, but making them work better for people. He rode the wave from web design to UX/UI, and finally to the more holistic field of Experience Design.\n\nA key turning point was a project redesigning the entire visitor journey for a popular science museum. He focused on everything from the ticketing queue and wayfinding signage to the flow of the interactive exhibits. The project\u2019s success cemented his reputation, leading to his current role as Head of Experience Design for a hospitality group that manages boutique hotels and acclaimed restaurants.\n\nNow 46, Kevin\u2019s life is a curated San Francisco experience. His day starts with a 3.1-mile e-bike commute from his Hayes Valley condo to his SoMa office, often with a stop for an oat milk latte. He\u2019s divorced\u2014an amicable split years ago\u2014and maintains a close circle of friends from his design and food-scene worlds. His connection to San Francisco is tactile; he loves the fog rolling over Twin Peaks and the distinct character of each neighborhood he bikes through.\n\nHis aspiration isn\u2019t a tech-bro exit strategy. Instead, Kevin dreams of leading a project with real civic impact\u2014redesigning the experience of a public space like the Ferry Building or a major park, leaving a beautiful, functional, and lasting mark on the city that shaped him."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "**1. Age 11 (c. 1989)**\nHe remembers sitting on the floor with The Cure\u2019s *Disintegration* LP sleeve, tracing the blurred, abstract art. His mother commented on its moody beauty, while his father, peering over his newspaper, noted the clean typography. In that moment, Kevin realized design was a language that could bridge their two worlds\u2014the emotional and the structural. It wasn\u2019t just about looking cool; it was about communicating a feeling with precision. It was a code he was determined to crack, a way to make sense of everything without needing the right words.\n\n**2. Age 24 (c. 2002)**\nThe dot-com bust had him designing a menu for a struggling trattoria in North Beach. Huddled with the owner over a sticky table at 1 AM, Kevin rearranged pasta dishes not for aesthetics, but for survival. Seeing the owner\u2019s relief when the new layout made specials pop was a revelation. For the first time, his design wasn't just decoration; it was a functional tool that could directly ease someone\u2019s burden. That feeling of tangible utility was more addictive than any creative award he could imagine.\n\n**3. Age 35 (c. 2013)**\nMonths after his team\u2019s museum redesign went live, he stood anonymously near the entrance, watching families. He saw a dad, kids in tow, navigate the new ticketing kiosk and digital map with zero friction. There was no confusion, no frustration\u2014just a seamless transition from the city street into a world of wonder. A wave of profound, quiet satisfaction washed over him. He hadn't just designed a system; he had designed a better start to someone\u2019s treasured memory. This was the scale he wanted to work at.\n\n**4. Age 39 (c. 2017)**\nThe end of his marriage wasn't a shouting match but a quiet conversation over coffee in Hayes Valley. On a napkin, he and his wife sketched out their separation like a user flow diagram: assets, communication protocols, next steps. It was deeply sad, yet imbued with a familiar sense of collaborative problem-solving. They were redesigning their life together into a life apart. It crystalized his belief that empathy and clear design could bring grace to even the most painful human experiences.\n\n**5. Age 45 (c. 2023)**\nHe was e-biking home as thick fog consumed the Ferry Building, blurring its iconic clock tower. He saw tourists squinting at confusing signs and locals weaving impatiently through the disorganized crowds. A sudden, intense ache of purpose hit him. This wasn\u2019t just a landmark; it was a flawed experience, a beautiful system crying out for a better design. He didn\u2019t just want to live in San Francisco; he wanted to fix its broken corners and make its beauty effortless for everyone."
